04489nam a22006855i 9786155053696DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222005hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97861550536967 a10.1515/97861550536962doi  a(DE-B1597)633569  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aUA646.8b.C37 2005eb 7aHIS0370702bisacsh04a355/.031/094722202aA Cardboard Castle? :bAn Inside History of the Warsaw Pact, 1955-1991 /ced. by Vojtech Mastny, Malcolm Byrne. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (786 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational Security Archive Cold War Reader00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tEditors’ Preface and Acknowledgements -- tAcronyms and Abbreviations -- tChronology of Events -- tThe Warsaw Pact as History -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE – THE FORMATIVE YEARS -- tPART TWO – THE CRISIS -- tPART THREE – THE ALLIANCE AT ITS PEAK -- tPART FOUR – THE INCIPIENT DECLINE -- tPART FIVE – DISINTEGRATION -- tMain Actors -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first book to document, analyze, and interpret the history of the Warsaw Pact based on the archives of the alliance itself. As suggested by the title, the Soviet bloc military machine that held the West in awe for most of the Cold War does not appear from the inside as formidable as outsiders often believed, nor were its strengths and weaknesses the same at different times in its surprisingly long history, extending for almost half a century. The introductory study by Mastny assesses the controversial origins of the "superfluous" alliance, its subsequent search for a purpose, its crisis and consolidation despite congenital weaknesses, as well as its unexpected demise. Most of the 193 documents included in the book were top secret and have only recently been obtained from Eastern European archives by the PHP project. The majority of the documents were translated specifically for this volume and have never appeared in English before. The introductory remarks to individual documents by co-editor Byrne explain the particular significance of each item. A chronology of the main events in the history of the Warsaw Pact, a list of its leading officials, a selective multilingual bibliography, and an analytical index add to the importance of a publication that sets the new standard as a reference work on the subject and facilitate its use by both students and general readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCold War. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aCold War, Communism, Eastern Europe, Military History, NATO, Sources, Warsaw Pact.1 aByrne, Malcolm, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMastny, Vojtech, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMastny, Vojtech, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978615505369640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9786155053696423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9786155053696/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK